I can not believe I have been on this yoga path for 28 days and today, instead of coming to the mat early, I made it in the late afternoon and by that point this is what I needed.

I am sure that the last few videos are not very long ones because it feels as though we come to the mat and 10 minutes later the session finishes.  

I am counting down the last days and I am going to take on the next challenge because I am feeling as though these 30 minutes I spend doing these practices have helped me through my day.  I had been lacking motivation when it comes to exercising and for other things in my life, but by doing this challenge it made me committed to keep coming back each day and spending 30 minutes focusing on my wellbeing.  It is also at a really good pace and at times the moves are challenging but I stay with the programme as there are things that are easy to do.  It has given me a new perspective as to what yoga is and how it can be used in your everyday.  I am definitely more aware of my breathing and from doing these moves, I am finding that I am able to do things I hadn't been able to do in a long time, especially when it comes to squatting down and not becoming breathless.

I can't believe I just finished day 28. I don't think I've ever done 28 days of anything, and here I am in sight of the 31 day finish line. I've been doing this practice in August, one of the hottest months of summer here. There have been days when my back sticks to my mat with sweat. There have been days when sweat is literally trickling down my body. There have been multiple days when I've had to do it directly in front of a giant fan. There have been days when I've cried with frustration trying to hold poses that push my limits. There have been days when I just couldn't go through with a pose that I'd done multiple times before. There have been days when I've lost my balance and toppled into walls. And beds. And dressers. And couches. There were four days when I was on vacation, and I brought my yoga mat with me so I could do yoga every day I was away from home. I've had no idea what's kept me coming back until Adriene said today that we are working with our bodies and not on our bodies. My initial goal starting this 31 days was to work on flexibility. Work on flexibility. My new goal, starting today and hopefully continuing beyond the 31 days, is to work WITH my flexibility--in my body and in my life in general.  I am finally finding what feels good! Namaste.

What I love about yoga is that there are days when I really don't feel like getting on the mat, but those are really the most important days because it's a day to just observe the mind really not wanting to practice.  

A day or a few days later, I'll be craving the mat again, knowing that at some point there will be the days that I really don't feel like the mat but understanding that's all part of the experience and part of a 'normal' mind.  I think this is why people give things up so easily (exercise, yoga, diets etc) - they hit that natural patch of 'demotivation' and throw in the towel when those are the days where you really learn so much about yourself. 

Today, I loved and craved this practice.  Last week, I was struggling to get on the mat and my mind felt tired and frustrated.  Both days, equally valuable.
Thank you Adriene :-) <3

I have been following your channel since my second knee surgery, after which I realized I needed to mend my relationship with my body as much as I needed to heal my knee. Two surgeries in a year is a lot for a knee and a spirit to tackle. But I did it. Yoga is one of the things that has helped me the most in repairing my relationship with my body, but this 31 day series is the first time I have done it so consistently. The change I have experienced is profound. Things that were physically out of reach I am now accomplishing with relative ease (crow pose is a perfect example). Much as I have gotten stronger, I am also trusting my body more, trusting myself more. 
If no one else has said it (and I am sure they have, actually), never underestimate the incredible force for good you are putting in the world with your yoga teaching. Thank you.
